          "title": "The six measures — a pledge that carries a promise",
          "body": "Before Ruth leaves the threshing floor, Boaz sends her away with six measures of barley (3:15, 17). The weight is significant — commentators estimate six seahs at roughly 90-100 pounds, a deliberate extravagance that could not be carried as casual gleaning. Boaz himself explains the gift's meaning: 'do not go to your mother-in-law empty-handed' (3:17). The word 'empty' (*reqam*) is the same word Naomi used of herself in 1:21 — 'the LORD has brought me back empty.' The six measures are Boaz's answer to Naomi's emptiness before the legal process is complete. The barley is a pledge — not the redemption itself, but the surety of it. Boaz cannot yet publicly act (the nearer redeemer must first be offered the right), but he can already act generously, and the generosity is itself covenantal. The greater Redeemer who Boaz foreshadows does not make His people wait empty-handed for their final inheritance; He gives the Spirit as a pledge (*arrabon*) of what is coming (Ephesians 1:14)."
