        "number": 3,
        "title": "The oath and the obstacle — integrity resolves the complication",
        "range": "3:11-13",
        "excerpt": "Now it is true I am a close relative; however, there is a relative closer than I.",
        "body": "Verses 11-13 are the chapter's legal and theological core. Boaz moves from blessing (v. 10) to commitment (v. 11) to complication (v. 12) to oath (v. 13) in four rapid movements. The sequence is not hesitation; it is integrity navigating a genuine obstacle with the highest available commitment.\n\n'Do not fear' (3:11) is Boaz's first word of resolution — spoken before the complication is named. This sequencing is significant. Boaz is not saying 'do not fear unless there is a problem'; he is saying 'do not fear' as an unconditional assurance, and then naming the problem within that assurance. The ground of his reassurance is community testimony: 'all my people in the city know that you are a woman of excellence (*eshet chayil*).' Boaz's commitment is not merely personal affection; it is grounded in his recognition of Ruth's established reputation. He will do whatever she asks because she is the kind of person whose asks deserve to be honored.\n\nThen the complication: 'there is a relative closer than I' (3:12). The existence of a nearer *goel* is not a surprise to Boaz — he has known about this man throughout the harvest season and has apparently not acted, perhaps because Ruth's willingness to be redeemed was not yet expressed. The nearer redeemer must be given first right. This is not a bureaucratic inconvenience; it is the same covenant order that Boaz has honored in every act of the book. He will not override another man's legal rights even when he desires to act himself.\n\nThe oath of 3:13 — 'as the LORD lives, I will redeem you' — is the chapter's climax. Swearing 'as the LORD lives' (*chai Adonai*) is the strongest oath form in the Hebrew Bible, invoking God's living existence as the guarantor of the speaker's commitment. It is the oath form used by Samuel (1 Samuel 14:39), by David (2 Samuel 4:9), and repeatedly in the prophets. Boaz is not making a polite promise; he is binding himself with a divine covenant oath. The complication did not weaken his commitment; it occasioned the most binding form of it. This is the portrait of a man whose integrity runs all the way down.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Chayil* (excellence/valor) — the same word used in Proverbs 31:10 (*eshet chayil*, 'woman of valor/excellence'). *Gaal* (redeem/kinsman-redeemer) clusters six times in vv. 12-13. *Chai Adonai* ('as the LORD lives') — the strongest oath formula in the Hebrew Bible, invoking God's living existence as guarantee."
